If there are any other coffee aficionados who happen to find this page, a simple work around seems to be to create a custom loader for webpack:

```
// fastCoffeeLoader.js
module.exports = function fastCoffeeLoader(source) {
  return source.replace(/^([A-Z]\w+)\s=\sfunction/gm, 'var $1 = function');
}

// next.config.js
module.exports = (phase, { defaultConfig }) => {
	return {
	  reactStrictMode: true,
		pageExtensions: ['coffee', 'jsx', 'js', 'ts', 'tsx'],

		webpack(config, options) {
			const { dir, defaultLoaders } = options
			config.resolve.extensions.push('.coffee')

			config.module.rules.push({
				test: /\.(coffee)$/,
				include: [dir],
				exclude: /node_modules/,
				use: [
					defaultLoaders.babel,
					{loader: path.resolve(__dirname, './fastCoffeeLoader.js')} // <----------
					{loader: 'coffee-loader'},

				]
```

It turns the output of coffee-loader:

```
var Hello, normalFunction;
Hello = function Hello() { ...
normalFunction = function normalFunction() { ...
```

into

```
var Hello, normalFunction;
var Hello = function() {...
normalFunction = function normalFunction() { ...
```

before passing it into the `defaultLoaders.babel` who then does its magic and adds the `var _c1;$RefreshReg$(_c1, "Hello");` stuff and hot refresh starts to work while preserving state in coffee components too.

Hi,

I had the same issue recently and went down the rabbit hole to understand it. I came up with 2 options:

1. Don't use `getServerSideProps` where you want restoration to work and don't enable the experimental scroll restoration. This is how scroll restoration works perfectly on this example
https://next-blog-wordpress.vercel.app/
https://github.com/vercel/next.js/tree/canary/examples/cms-wordpress
Without the experimental scroll restoration browser's native `window.history.scrollRestoration` set to `auto` handles page refreshes like you said. When it comes to navigation scroll restoration it's working because the props for the page are cached when you are using `getStaticProps` so the default browser's implementation can handle that too. At least that's what came up with testing it. I couldn't find any documentation about this caching so there may be cases where it doesn't work. I suspect that without cache the restoration happens during the pending request and the result seems like it haven't been restored. I didn't find any way of caching `getServerSideProps` props on client side.

2. Enable experimental scroll restoration and handle the page refresh case on your own. This is what I went with since switching from `getServerSideProps` to `getStaticProps` was not an option for me. As far as I can tell the experimental implementation of scroll restoration doesn't handle refresh case by design https://github.com/vercel/next.js/commit/38bd1a024cb25923d8ea15f269a7294d073684d8. I came up with a hook that I call in `_app.js`.
```
import { useEffect } from 'react';
import { throttle } from 'throttle-debounce';

function useRefreshScrollRestoration() {
    useEffect(() => {
        const pageAccessedByReload = window.performance
            .getEntriesByType('navigation')
            .map((nav) => nav.type)
            .includes('reload');

        if (pageAccessedByReload) {
            const scrollPosition = Number.parseInt(sessionStorage.getItem('scrollPosition'), 10);
            if (scrollPosition) {
                window.scrollTo(0, scrollPosition);
            }
        }

        const handleScroll = throttle(500, () => {
            sessionStorage.setItem('scrollPosition', window.scrollY);
        });

        window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);

        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
        };
    }, []);
}

export default useRefreshScrollRestoration;
```

I hope this helps you out.

