Hi, the reason is that you have a `index.test.js` file inside `pages`, and by default, all `.js` files will be included at build-time and considered as page routes. Since that file contains `describe` (which is specific to Jest tests), the build will fail. To mitigate this, you have two options:

1. move the test file outside of the `pages` directory
2. Use the `pageExtensions` config option to specify which files should be considered pages routes.
One way is to do something like this:
```js
module.exports = {
  pageExtensions: ['jsx'],
};
```

and rename all your page files to end with `.jsx` instead of `.js`

Another is to add a suffix to your pages, something like `.page`, (eg. `index.page.js`) with the following:
```js
module.exports = {
  pageExtensions: ['pages.js'],
};
```

For more information, check out our docs page! :pray: https://nextjs.org/docs/api-reference/next.config.js/custom-page-extensions#including-non-page-files-in-the-pages-directory

