Not 100% sure I followed what you're asking, but since dynamic pages export a `getStaticPaths` function, you can reuse that same function since it's what Next.js would call to generate your pages anyways. Here's an example:

```
// in your api/revalidate.js file

import { getStaticPaths } from 'pages/articles/[slug]'

export default async function revalidate(req, res) {
  try {
    // grab static paths using the same method Next.js would use
    const staticPaths = await getStaticPaths()

    // get an array of promises
    const revalidatePaths = staticPaths.map((path) =>
          res.unstable_revalidate(`/articles/${path.params.slug}`)
    );

    // run revalidation in parallel
    await Promise.all([res.unstable_revalidate('/articles'), ...revalidatePaths]);
    
    return res.status(200).send()
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(err)
    return res.status(500).send('Revalidation Error')
  }

}
```

If you need to revalidate multiple dynamic pages, you can always create a generic `getAllStaticPaths` functions that basically just calls `getStaticPaths` from all of your pages and creates one big path array, like below:

```
import { getStaticPaths as getArticlePaths } from 'pages/articles/[slug]';
import { getStaticPaths as getContactPaths } from 'pages/contacts/[[...slug]]';
import { getStaticPaths as getCountryPaths } from 'pages/countries/[slug]';

export async function getAllStaticPaths() {
  const res = await Promise.all([getArticlePaths(), getContactPaths(), getCountryPaths()]);
  const articlePaths = res[0].paths.map((path) => `/articles/${path.params.slug}`);
  const contactPaths = res[1].paths.map((path) => `/contacts/${path.params.slug}`);
  const countryPaths = res[2].paths.map((path) => `/countries/${path.params.slug}`);

  return articlePaths.concat(contactPaths).concat(countryPaths);
}
```

Of course, this is very manual, but you can probably get fancy and automate this for all pages by dynamically importing each page as a module (using a library like `import-glob`) and extracting the `getStaticPaths` method. The hard part is prepending the proper path prefix (ie. `/articles` or `/file/[folderSlug]/[fileSlug]`). Here's some partially completed code to give you an idea:

**WARNING: This code doesn't work, it's just a demo of an idea**
```
import allPages from './pages/**/*.js` // need the import-glob library installed for this

