Before I was preloading some fonts using `<link>` at `_document.tsx` like this:

```tsx
// _document.tsx
<link
  rel="preload"
  href="/css/fonts/font.woff2"
  as="font"
  crossOrigin=""
/>
```

The approach above is a best practice for FCP, but it's **unnecessary with Next.js**. So we don't need to do it using Next.js.

Unfortunately I did not find this information at Next documentation, but I found for **local fonts** only for web fonts [here](https://nextjs.org/docs/basic-features/font-optimization)).

So, seems the _"right"_ way (I mean right way here because fixed my problem), to do it right with Next is by just importing css with font face instruction form the app file.

First, import the css with font face instructions from `_app.tsx` (or `_app.js`).
```tsx
// _app.tsx or _app.js

import '../css/fonts.css'
```

Then, ensure to have proper `@font-face` configured to load fonts locally

```css
/* fonts.css */
@font-face {
  font-family: 'Some Font';
  font-style: normal;
  font-weight: 300;
  font-display: swap;
  src: local(''), url('/fonts/font.woff2') format('woff2'),
    url('/fonts/font.woff') format('woff');
}
```
References:
[Next.js - Font Optimization](https://nextjs.org/docs/basic-features/font-optimization)
