Alright, I spent actually a lot of hours tinkering around with next config and individual files.

I found out what the issue was - given I was previously using the Next.js 12.0 build, in order to opt-in to the concurrent features, you had to add

```js
// next.config.js
module.exports = {
  experimental: {
     concurrentFeatures: true,
  }
  // ...
}
```

In order to enable them. However in Next.js 12.1 this has been deperecated as pointed out [here](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/pull/34068) and should now be replaced with `runtime` experimental flag.

> Nextjs on running dev does technically throw an error if you have concurrentFeatures enabled that a `runtime` flag is now required, however it still allows you to run the next application without removing the `concurrentFeatures` flag, which was cuasing issues with the build.

Changing your `next.config.js` to

```js
// next.config.js
module.exports = {
  experimental: {
     runtime: 'edge', // or runtime: 'nodejs'
  }
  // ...
}
```

fixes the issue, that being said, there should probably be a warning raised when these conflicting flags exist or at the very least this should be listed as a breaking change in changelog from 12.0 to 12.1

