Hi,

I have now taken a tour through your project. 

### A quick patch

1. Use an `article` instead of a `div`
```jsx
// pages/posts/[id].js
 <article
        className="prose lg:prose-xl"
        dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: postData.contentHtml }}
      />

```

2.  Remove the article tag from the `md` file. 

The thing with Tailwind, is that in order to decide what CSS should be used, the class strings have to be present in your JS/TS/JSX/TSX/HTML/CSS code. They can be defined dynamically, but must be whole. For example:

```js
//  ✔️ works!
const className  = isLarge ? "text-lg" : "text-sm";
// ❌ doesn't work!
const cn = `text-${isLarge ? 'lg' : 'sm'}`
```
I think when starting with Tailwind, this doesn't come as intuitively as it should.

So it's best to define these things in your JavaScript files.

Most markdown processors protect against XSS by removing tags that are not allowed/expected. Forcing yourself to manage that every time you publish something is not desirable, I'd say.

### Alternative

If you want to write more complex blog posts, with free range on which HTML tags, or even use JSX components. I'd recommend these changes:

1. Switch to `next-mdx-remote` (or any tool that can do mdx, which is a superset of md), in this case `yarn add next-mdx-remote --exact`
2. Adapt your parser
```js
