I found this from [NextJS Docs](https://nextjs.org/docs/going-to-production#caching)

```js
// This value is considered fresh for ten seconds (s-maxage=10).
// If a request is repeated within the next 10 seconds, the previously
// cached value will still be fresh. If the request is repeated before 59 seconds,
// the cached value will be stale but still render (stale-while-revalidate=59).
//
// In the background, a revalidation request will be made to populate the cache
// with a fresh value. If you refresh the page, you will see the new value.
export async function getServerSideProps({ req, res }) {
  res.setHeader(
    'Cache-Control',
    'public, s-maxage=10, stale-while-revalidate=59'
  )

  return {
    props: {},
  }
}
```

> If the request is repeated before 59 seconds, the cache value will be stale ... in the background a revalidation request will be made ...

According to [web.dev](https://web.dev/stale-while-revalidate/), a request made outside of the window of `max-age` and `stale-while-revalidate` will deem the cache stale and abandon it for the fresh value. That would be useful in `getStaticProps`, but I haven't seen any option to specify that for when it runs on revalidation. 

All `Cache-Control` headers specified in `next.config.js` are overwritten in production, so thats not an option either.

