If you are thinking that your Next.js instance should have the `GraphQL` endpoint, I have to warn you that, that's not necessarily possible.

At build time, there's no lambdas, in fact, there's no running server, so even if you had `api/graphl`, such endpoint will be non-existent. 

This is why, `URLs` ought to be absolute when using `fetch` inside `getStaticProps` and `getServerSideProps`. Note that even `axios` won't help you (Next.js polyfills fetch for node), it'll just not find the endpoint needed. 

So in short, the idea of having  an `api/graphql` endpoint exposed by your application to render on demand is not so easily done, and it is not possible at build time. You'd need to have access on `getServerSideProps` to the absolute URL of your application, any relative paths will just fail.

You could however, on `getStaticProps` or `getServeSideProps` connect to the external resource, or use `cwd` like so https://nextjs.org/docs/api-reference/data-fetching/get-static-props#reading-files-use-processcwd, to read from the file system.

```js
// or getStaticProps
export const getServerSideProps = async () => {
  const res = await fs.readFile(
    path.resolve(process.cwd(), "public", "waves.min.svg"),
    "utf-8"
  );

  return { props: { } };
}
```

To send a GraphQL request, it's just a `POST` request, with the query and variables as body payload.

