The issue occurs because of the `isOBS` variable that will obviously be different between the server and the client.
This variable is responsible for rendering some part of your component.

A solution that could help is to set the "obs" value inside a useEffect (to make sure that it is only called client-side).

Instead of having:
```js
const isOBS = useMemo(() => (isBrowser ? navigator?.userAgent?.indexOf('OBS') !== -1 : false), [isBrowser]);
```

it'd be something like:
```js
const [isOBS, setIsOBS] = useState(false);

useEffect(() => {
  setIsOBS(isBrowser ? navigator?.userAgent?.indexOf('OBS') !== -1 : false);
 }, [isBrowser]);
```

This way, the value is false by default, and the server will render the "false" state, which will be hydrated by the client.
Once the hydration is over, the useEffect will be ran, and the layout will change if it needs to.

