It seems to me that this is not a use case for `getServerSideProps`, because the SEO relevant parts are known at "build" time or at "ISR" time, while the additional layer of user bound data is not SEO relevant. 

You should make your page so that it can fetch the user layer data from the client, using SWR, React Query, Redux, etc, and have an initial state for the post page which reflects what should search engines, crawlers and the rest see. 

I think with the upcoming React 18, this could also be done in a better way, but for now I'd say, pre-render or ISR, these pages, and for each user, from the client, fetch data based on their session. You can prepare another endpoint on `api/post/user-data` or such, where you go and fetch the data you need from your database. This is very similar to what you'd do in CSR, except you don't start with zero HTML, but you have the relevant meta tags, and initial HTML that's independent of who's reading it.

You cannot do the blocking false thing, ever, because `getServerSideProps` has to render the entire HTML string on the server, and then send it downstream. 

This is not a problem with Next.js, but it is a pitfall of any approach that renders on demand, https://github.com/reactwg/react-18/discussions/37. A solution, repeating myself here, is to pre-render as much as possible at built time or ISR, making sure that the pre-rendered page has the capability to fetch data and update itself. 

