@andre7000 to dynamically import a **Component** from node_modules, you can just `dynamic(()=>import("name_of_module_with_component"))`, and pass the flags you need, for example `ssr:false`.

However, it might be better to dynamically import **your component**, because otherwise you'd be pressed to do checks on whether or not the library **Component** has loaded. So I'd take your second option:

```tsx
const DynamicComponentWithNoSSR = dynamic(
() => import("../components/recordRTC/RecordRTCItem"),
{ ssr: false }
);
```

> **Note that you wouldn't need `dynamic` to import `lodash`, just `import()`. Please do read the [docs](https://nextjs.org/docs/advanced-features/dynamic-import).**

For arguments sake, if you were dynamically importing `lodash` and only used it in Component A, then you need to have checks all over the place in Component A, to make sure `lodash` is now present. Instead, if the entire Component A is dynamically loaded, then your code can just assume `lodash` is present, if Component A is loaded.

Do be careful with bundling, simply dynamically importing doesn't mean some part of the library won't be bundled, or try to run at build time. For example if you, have Component A, dynamically imported, but something else from that module is statically imported to the "main" bundle, then you'd force the dependencies of Component A to be bundled into main.

To the point of `TypeError: document.querySelector is not a function.`, if it's coming from `styled-jsx` then we are surely in a pickle, because this code is guarded against direct window checks, by `typeof window !=== 'undefined'`.

