@umerjaved178 - You can either:

- Initialise the custom hook to a sensible default, independent of the environment, aka no document, and update it inside a `useEffect`, which is guaranteed to run on the client only
- Hide the component using the custom hook behind a client side flag:
```tsx
function Parent() {
  const [showChild, setShowChild] = useState(false);
  // Wait until after client-side hydration to show
  useEffect(() => {
    setShowChild(true);
  }, []);

  // You can show some kind of placeholder UI here
  if (!showChild) return null;
 // offending Child that needs to know the browser runtime
  return <Child />;
}
```
- Use lazy state initialisation:
```tsx
const useLocationhost = () => {
    const [value, setValue] = useState(() => typeof window !== 'undefined' ? document.location.host : "");
    useEffect(() => {
     // if the `useState` did find document, React bails out on this update
      setValue(()=> document.location.host)
     },[]);
    return value; // you do have to check for "" (empty strings) when using this hook
}
```

All cases require you to have `window`/`document` guarded access. 


This is not a Next.js limitation, but an SSR requirement because of Isomorphic (universal) JavaScript. The server, must be able to render the "dry" first frame HTML of your site. Using hooks that directly check on document/window or DOM elements, breaks this, and it is a common pitfall when learning to use SSR.

