Hi,

The issue is that when the route handlers, pages, etc, code is loaded - any top level statements are also run.

In your case, the `getDbUrl` function is called here:

```ts
const client = postgres(getDbUrl(), {
  prepare: false,
  max: 25, 
  idle_timeout: 60,
  max_lifetime: 60 * 60, 
  ssl: false,
});
```

And I guess this is part of a route handler's top level scope. 

If you were to do:

```ts
export const db = () => { 
   const client = postgres(getDbUrl(), {
     prepare: false,
     max: 25, 
     idle_timeout: 60,
     max_lifetime: 60 * 60, 
     ssl: false,
   });
   return drizzle(client, { schema });
}
```

Essentially turning it into a getter, then you can `db()` inside the body of a Route Handler, or Page, and it would be fine, if it is force dynamic and such.

My problem was a file that used to import an async connection from the db and export a var with that connection already working. I've changed to a singleton and whoever wants the same "var" now needs to get the db instance.

From

```ts
import { getDbConnection } from "@/modules/database";

export const db = await getDbConnection()
```

To

```ts
import { getDbConnection, Database } from "@/modules/database";

class DatabaseSingleton {
  private static instance: DatabaseSingleton;
  private db: Database | null = null;

  private constructor() {}

  public static getInstance(): DatabaseSingleton {
    if (!DatabaseSingleton.instance) {
      DatabaseSingleton.instance = new DatabaseSingleton();
    }
    return DatabaseSingleton.instance;
  }

  public async getDatabase(): Promise<Database> {
    if (!this.db) {
      this.db = await getDbConnection();
    }
    return this.db;
  }
}

export const db = async () => {
  const dbSingleton = DatabaseSingleton.getInstance();
  return await dbSingleton.getDatabase();
}
```

