This is a normal "error" when running tests with a production build.
That being said, it should only be a console.error and not a thrown error.

If you really want to use production code for testing purposes, you could ignore the error like:
```js
// hide error messages about act() being unsupported in production build
const ignoredErrors = [
  /act(...) is not supported in production builds of React, and might not behave as expected./,
]
const consoleError = global.console.error
global.console.error = (...args) => {
  if (!ignoredErrors.find((el) => el.test(args[0]))) {
    return consoleError(...args)
  }
}

```
in a jest [setupFiles](https://jestjs.io/docs/configuration#setupfiles-array).

Whilst the solution here isn't ideal I found myself needing it for a specific use-case. It also didn't work for me without some changes

You would need to escape the ( and . characters. Also when the test matches is where we should ignore the error (in my case I change it to a regular console log).

```
const ignoredErrors = [
  /act\(\.\.\.\) is not supported in production builds of React/,
];

const consoleError = global.console.error;
global.console.error = (...args) => {
  if (ignoredErrors.some((el) => el.test(args[0]))) {
    return console.log(...args); 
  }
  return consoleError(...args);
};
```

