_`Error: Hydration failed because the initial UI does not match what was rendered on the server.`_
`_next-dev.js?3515:25 Warning: Text content did not match. Server: "🌙" Client: "☀️"_`
_`Uncaught Error: There was an error while hydrating. Because the error happened outside of a Suspense boundary, the entire root`_

Here's a little on how Hydration works with the client/server: https://blog.saeloun.com/2021/12/16/hydration.html

### This is the clarification provided on Next-Themes:

```
Warning! The above code is hydration unsafe and will throw a hydration mismatch warning when rendering with SSG or SSR. This is because we cannot know the theme on the server, so it will always be undefined until mounted on the client.

You should delay rendering any theme toggling UI until mounted on the client. See the [example](https://www.npmjs.com/package/next-themes?activeTab=readme#avoid-hydration-mismatch).

To fix this, make sure you only render UI that uses the current theme when the page is mounted on the client.
```

**SOLUTION: After reviewing how React SSR Hydration works, my solution was this:**

```js
import { useTheme } from 'next-themes';
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

const ToggleButton: React.FunctionComponent = () => {
  const [mounted, setMounted] = useState(false);
  const { theme, setTheme } = useTheme();

  useEffect(() => setMounted(true), []);
  if (!mounted) return null;

  return (
    <div className="flex items-center justify-center">
      <button
        type="button"
        aria-label="Light and Dark Mode Toggle Button"
        className="inline-flex items-center px-3 py-2 shadow-sm text-xs font-medium rounded bg-white hover:scale-110 duration-500"
        onClick={() => setTheme(theme === 'dark' ? 'light' : 'dark')}
      >
        {theme === 'light' ? '☀️' : '🌙'}
      </button>
    </div>
  );
};

export default ToggleButton;
```

