You have to use `typeof window !== 'undefined'` or any of those checks, which are doing something called "Guard DOM access". 

Any library that wants to have SSR compatibility needs to avoid setting state initialisers (or doing any work really) without guarded DOM access. Simply put, the server cannot make any assumptions about the runtime because it has no knowledge about it. 

```ts
// don't
const [value, setValue] = useState(window.someproperty); // or direct document check
// maybe...
const [value, setValue] = useState(() => {
  if(typeof window !== 'undefined') return window.someprop; // keeps it compatible for folks using CSR
  return false; // a sensible fallback or initial value for folks using SSR
})
```

You can also activate your component by placing it behind a client side activated flag, and avoid breaking it into different bundle.

```tsx
const [show, setShow] = useState(false)

useEffect(() => setShow(true),[]);

return show && <ChildWithoutGuardedDOMAccess />
```

This is one of the challenges/pitfalls of moving from CSR to SSR.

Inside `useEffect` it is possible to assume that window/document will be present, because it runs client side.

