Hi,

Since `gSSP` runs on the server, why not use `path` and `__filename`?

```tsx
// pages/posts/[...slug].tsx
import path from "path";

const Foo = () => <div>Foo</div>;

export default Foo;

export const getServerSideProps = () => {
  console.log("__filename", path.basename(__filename));
  return { props: {} };
};
```

- `__filename` is injected by Node.js, similarly to `__dirname`, read: https://nodejs.org/api/modules.html#the-module-wrapper
- Notice that it will log `[...slug].js`, a `js` extension, and not `tsx`

Alternatively, to keep the actual extension:

```tsx
// pages/posts/[...slug].tsx
import path from "path";

const Foo = () => <div>Foo</div>;

export default Foo;

export const getServerSideProps = () => {
  const __filename = new URL("", import.meta.url).pathname;
  console.log("__filename", path.basename(__filename));
  return { props: {} };
};
```

If you want to see the `dirname`, use directly `__dirname` or `path.dirname(__filename)`.

The second approach might be more resilient in an ES modules era though.

You could also derive this info from `params`, by listing its own properties, which should be something like:

```shell
{ slug: [ 'a', 'b', 'c' ] }
```

But I guess that'd be very complex code, compared to just using the Node.js API.

