I now have to vouch for this. We have a top level middleware that makes sure certain query parameter is never present, among other things. We centralized all cases through a rewrite.

Now, we want to use nested middleware, but because of the top level rewrite, the downstream middleware doesn't get triggered. 

This solution does work though. Taken from [here](https://github.com/vercel/examples/blob/main/edge-functions/query-params-filter/pages/_middleware.ts).

```ts
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server'

const allowedParams = ['allowed']

export function middleware(req: NextRequest) {
  const url = req.nextUrl
  let changed = false

  url.searchParams.forEach((_, key) => {
    if (!allowedParams.includes(key)) {
      url.searchParams.delete(key)
      changed = true
    }
  })

  // Avoid infinite loop by only redirecting if the query
  // params were changed
  if (changed) {
    return NextResponse.redirect(url)
  }
 // otherwise do our rewrite logic
}
```

However, that, `changed` variable, does feel odd, and we now trigger a client side redirect.

