There's a few things here, the `getLayout` function is not a React component, and therefore, it should not have any "react" logic within its definition. These functions exist only to template how the page would look like, not its logic.

This article, https://kentcdodds.com/blog/dont-call-a-react-function-component, by Kent C Dodds, talks about the opposite issue, when a React component is used as a function. If my assumption is correct, the issue you are facing the problems of treating a function as a React component.

> Notice that `getLayout` doesn't take `props` as input, but `page`

The Next.js docs are very subtle about this in the, https://nextjs.org/docs/basic-features/layouts#data-fetching, section. You are expected to define a component layout (which might include other siblings/children), which contains logic, data-fetching, etc., and you tell Next.js through `getLayout`, what to pass on to React to be rendered.

In your case, define each layout, with all of its React logic, as a component that might as well be used with another framework, and then define the `getLayout` function for the page that will use it, as a means to template/describe the looks for the page.

